I will attempt to show in rather simple (simplistic) terms why neutrality is an important concept in evolution and why neutrality itself (degeneracy) is an evolvable trait.

So let's start with the degeneracy of the <url href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genetic_code">genetic code</url>. As most people should know, the genetic code is read in triplets (three neighboring bases U C A or G). This means that there are 4<sup>3</sup> possible codes. However there are only 20 amino acids which means that multiple triplets all code for the same amino acid.

