Source: <url href="http://www.sparknotes.com/biology/molecular/geneticcode/section1.html">Spark Notes</url>

Now look carefully, the rows and columns represent the first and second nucleotide, this means that all triples in a single table cell are within one point mutation away from each-other (they only differ in the third position). Now take a particular example such as Leu (leucine), depending on the triplet which encodes for Leu, either Ser or Pro are within one point mutation from Leu but when Leu is encoded with UU in the first and second position, it is one mutation away from becoming a Stop Codon (UAA, UAG or UGA) when it is encoded by CU in the first and second position, it is one point mutation away from Pro, His or Gln or Arg. In other words, the genetic distance between two amino acids can be 1 to three mutations depending on the underlying coding of the triplet.


<!--more-->

